## Lesson 37-1: Introduction (rc/37-1.tsx)

### After the five-item purpose vocabulary:
{{+Add a "Passage Function vs. Main Point" comparison table: "These two question types are closely related and often confused. Main Point asks WHAT the author concludes. Passage Function asks WHY the author wrote the passage. For the same passage, the main point might be 'strict emissions standards are necessary,' while the purpose would be 'to argue for a specific policy change.'"+}}

### After the stem identification breakdown:
{{+Add a "Function Hierarchy" note: "This module completes a three-level progression. Phrase Function (Module 35) targets a specific detail. Paragraph Function (Module 36) targets an entire paragraph. Passage Function (this module) targets the whole text. Each level uses the same core skill — identifying authorial purpose — at a different scale."+}}

### Comparative Inquiry stem category:
{{+Expand with a brief note: "Comparative Passage Function questions add an extra layer: you must determine the purpose of each passage independently, then characterize how those purposes relate to each other. This often requires synthesizing two distinct authorial goals into a single comparative statement."+}}

